SIMPLE: shed
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shed
<hw>Shed</hw> <pr>(sh⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[The same word as
<ets>shade</ets>. See <er>Shade</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A slight
or temporary structure built to shade or shelter something; a structure
often open in front; an outbuilding; a hut; <as>as, a wagon
<ex>shed</ex>; a wood <ex>shed</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The first Aletes born in lowly <qex>shed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Sheds</qex> of reeds which summer's heat repel.</q>
<rj><qau>Sandys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Aeronautics)</fld> <def>A covered structure for
housing aircraft; a hangar.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shed
<hw>Shed</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shedding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>scheden</ets>,
<ets>sch<?/den</ets>, to pour, to part, AS. <ets>sc⟦amac⟧dan</ets>,
<ets>sce⟦aacute⟧dan</ets>, to pert, to separate; akin to OS.
<ets>sk<?/<?/an</ets>, OFries. sk<?/tha, G. <ets>scheiden</ets>, OHG.
<ets>sceidan</ets>, Goth. <ets>skaidan</ets>, and probably to Lith.
<ets>sk⟦eum⟧du</ets> I part, separate, L. <ets>scindere</ets> to cleave,
to split, Gr. <?/<?/<?/, Skr. <ets>chid</ets>, and perch. also to L.
<ets>caedere</ets> to cut. ⟦root⟧159. Cf. <er>Chisel</er>,
<er>Concise</er>, <er>Schism</er>, <er>Sheading</er>, <er>Sheath</er>,
<er>Shide</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To separate; to divide.</def>
<mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Robert of
Brunne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To part with; to throw off or give forth from one's
self; to emit; to diffuse; to cause to emanate or flow; to pour forth or
out; to spill; <as>as, the sun <ex>sheds</ex> light; she <ex>shed</ex>
tears; the clouds <ex>shed</ex> rain</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Did Romeo's hand <qex>shed</qex> Tybalt's blood?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Twice seven consenting years have <qex>shed</qex>⟦br⟧
Their utmost bounty on thy head.</q> <rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To let fall; to throw off, as a natural covering of
hair, feathers, shell; to cast; <as>as, fowls <ex>shed</ex> their
feathers; serpents <ex>shed</ex> their skins; trees <ex>shed</ex>
leaves</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cause to flow off without penetrating; <as>as, a
tight roof, or covering of oiled cloth, <ex>sheeds</ex>
water</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To sprinkle; to intersperse; to cover.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Her hair . . . is <xex>shed</xex> with
gray.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <def>To divide, as the warp threads,
so as to form a shed, or passageway, for the shuttle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shed
<hw>Shed</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fall in drops; to
pour.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such a rain down from the welkin <qex>shadde</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To let fall the parts, as seeds or fruit; to throw
off a covering or envelope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>White oats are apt to <qex>shed</qex> most as they lie, and black
as they stand.</q> <rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Shed
<hw>Shed</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A parting; a separation; a
division.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They say also that the manner of making the <qex>shed</qex> of
newwedded wives' hair with the iron head of a javelin came up then
likewise.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. North.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of shedding or spilling; -- used only in
composition, as in blood<xex>shed</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which parts, divides, or sheds; -- used in
composition, as in water<xex>shed</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <def>The passageway between the
threads of the warp through which the shuttle is thrown, having a
sloping top and bottom made by raising and lowering the alternate
threads.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shedder</ent>⟦br⟧
